postcontent:
Brand new scope. Never been mounted or used. Kept in box at all times. Retail price at Trijicon is $1550 and $1317.50 (green dot) at Amazon. Asking price $920+FREE SHIPPING.                                                                                        
The Accupoint 5-20X 50 Mil-Dot Crosshair Riflescope is Trijicon's longest-range scope ever. With advanced fiber optics, tritium aiming-point illumination, a huge 50-millimeter objective lens, and easy-to-use windage/elevation and parallax adjusters, the scope provides tactical shooters, varmint hunters, as well as law enforcement snipers the ability to accurately extend their range in any light. The scope comes equipped for any lighting conditions with a 3-inch sunshade. A 30-millimeter tube offers a greater range of mounting options and unmatched long eye relief of 3.8 to 4.1 inches, protects against the recoil of higher caliber rifles. And, the Accupoint's Tritium lamp operates entirely without batteries, eliminating the potential for failure during critical moments in the field.

The Accupoint is Illuminated through the use of fiber optics for automatic light adjustments and a built-in self-luminous Tritium Phospor Lamp. The powerful scope provides a vivid crosshair Mil-Dot aiming reticle with green illumination without the need for failure-prone batteries. A dual-illumination system automatically adjusts the aiming-point brightness to existing lighting conditions for a faster and easier performance in variable light. A manual brightness override allows shooters to easily adjust the reticle to suit their preferences. A multilayer-coated lens provides superior light transmission with no distortion and unsurpassed edge-to-edge optical clarity. The scope is equipped with easy-to-use external turret controls for windage and elevation adjustment and a side parallax adjuster for enhanced accuracy at long range.

Backed by a lifetime warranty that protects against manufacturer's defects, the Accupoint riflescope is crafted from aircraft-quality, hard-anodized aluminum with a tube that's nitrogen-filled to prevent corrosion and eliminate fogging. A solid black-matte finish eliminates glare and light reflection, which could spook game. Water resistant to depths of 10 feet, the Accupoint is able to handle even the most challenging hunting conditions.

The Accupoint 5-20X 50 Mil-dot Riflescope comes complete with a sunshade, a set of lenscaps, a lenspen, a Trijicon Logo Sticker, a manual, and warranty card. The Lenspen features a safe and easy to use retractable dust removal brush and a special non-liquid cleaning element, designed to never dry out. The die cut Trijicon Logo sticker measures at 3 x 2.75 inches and is made from durable red and black silk-screened 4-millimeter white opaque vinyl that can be applied to any flat surface for a permanent stick. The warranty covers the riflescope's metal structure and optics for lifetime and the Tritium Lamp for 15 years.

postcontent:
This is a custom made upper half for Armalite B models (uses their excellent steel magazines) w/ a 12.5" barrel.  It features the gas system of a Noveskie Leonidas, between carbine and mid length.  IIRC it gets like 94% of the power from the cartridge, >2400 fps even with 175 grain ammo.  Keeps your Suppressed OAL down

Aimpoin & mount NOT included.    

Obviously, I cannot sell a lower half w/ this upper nor can I knowingly sell the upper to a guy who has only non NFA AR10 rifle lowers to put it on.  But you can get a new stripped receiver for $228 on the internet +$25 dealer fee and do a pistol build w/ a sig arm brace.  You can just leave it as a "pistol" or you can later convert it to a SBR when you get a NFA Form 1 back from the ATF. 

That is a JP rifle lenght HG system.  I'll throw in a front sight rail and two 2" accessory rails, I belive I have a 4" rail too. It is painted OD green w/ Brownells Alumahyde. The HG is flush w/ the muzzle, but at least an inch of it can be ground off if you want to bring the HG back behind the shoulder to make clearance for a silencer mount or  whatever.  Shorter tubes can be purchased from JP for ca $80

The barrel was made from a brand new Armalite chrome lined 20" Hbar that I had cut, contoured, drilled & threaded by Adco.  The barrel is .750" from chamber to journal, then ca .740 to the muzzle shoulder, w/ standard 5/8" threads.  I had this made b/c I wanted something lighter than the noveskie upper, and with a more durable chrome bore, and that I could put a heat sink on so that the barrel would hopefully never have to be changed.  

Here is a google search pic of the "JP Thermal dissipator" heat sink


Upper is standard Armalite w/ regular chaging handle & BCG w/ recent version extractor & spring.  Lookign at it, it has some scuffs from rubbing on uther guns in the safe, but not too bad. 

Gas block is a Palladin Machine three position: unrestricted, suppressed & off. Here is a pic that looks similar.  A norrow flat head screwdriver easily fits in the handguard slot to adjust.


I should mention have an extra standard barrel nut and a T barrel nut in case you need them so you want it for a different handguard system.  I might consider selling parts if I can't sell the upper, but I have the gas block staked every which way and everything secure on there real well, it would be a hassle to dissassemble it when it is secured together and proved functional.  New gas tubes are availible if you want to use a new gas block.

Was planning on shipping w/o a muzzle device.  It has a Troy Claymore on it but would probably like to keep unless you really want it.  I also have a loose A2.

I have 678 rounds through it in the nearly 5 yrs since I put it together.  It runs perceftly, even w/ the suppressor on there w/ the adjustable gas block. 

Ultimately, the gun is just heavier than I wanted by the time I got it all accessorized and I'd rather sell and use the funds for some lighter weight AR15 projects.  W/ slash buffer, commercial AR15 M4 stock assembly (w/o saddle), the 2.8oz muzzle device, a couple sling studs it weigs 7.71 lbs, w/o sights.  Loose the heat sink and it comes down to about 7.5lbs. title: For Sale:  S&W M&P 10 brand new rifle w/ Ruger RDS
postcontent: I am selling a brand new Smith & Wesson M&P 10. This rifle is the best semi-automatic rifle ever built on the .308 / 7.62x51 NATO AR platform (just my opinion of course but I've shot every top of the line .308 built on this platform and this has outperformed them all). S&W began manufacturing these rifles last year in order to compete with the Armalite and Colt AR10 series rifles. They have went above and beyond what was needed to ensure the reliability and quality of these rifles. I currently own 2, one of which is mine that I will never be selling, and the other I purchased for my wife who ended up deciding to stick with her 5.56 and pass on the .308. The rifle comes with an ambidextrous safety, mag release and bolt release which definitely favors the left handed shooter. Being a righty I thought it would bother me as I consider myself somewhat close minded when parts on rifles change but to be 100 percent honest it's really nice to have these availabilities on both sides of the rifle. You never really know what situation may arise where you need these extra features. They never get in the way when handling to fire and fit very nicely into the design of the rifle. I have added the Ruger RDS (rapid deploy sights) which are similar to the magpul BUIS but I personally like the sight picture a little better on these. And I'm by no means saying they are superior to the magpul sights because I currently have those on one of my other rifles but in this instance I prefer the Ruger set up. In all honesty the reviews speak for them self for this thing and I'm disappointed she doesn't want to keep it but it's got to go. It comes with the hard carrying case, 20 rd. P-mag, manual and lock. I paid 1550 plus tax and an additional 70 for the front and rear sights. I don't intend on losing my ass on a brand new rifle so I took 25 off what I paid and I don't mind sitting until it's gone. I'm easy to deal with and am willing to meet anywhere you'd like. All I ask is to take a picture of your ID so after you leave I'm covered. Thank you for your consideration and please contact me through email.

title: For Sale:  WW2 P38: BYF 43 with original magazine and holster
postcontent:
Hello all and thanks for viewing. I have an original WW2 Nazi marked p38 pistol for sale. It is cambered in 9mm and is a single/ double action firearm with a de-cocker. Has a 5 inch barrel with a nice bluing for the finish and original black grips.

Has at least 80% bluing remaining and is in good shape considering its age. Perfect working condition with nice bore and crisp trigger pull. All original parts with matching numbers. This is a non-import p38 with no import marks on it. 

The firearm shoots very nice, functions great. However, because of its old age and historical value I do not recommend shooting this pistol but rather keeping it for collection purposes. It is a piece of history.

The p38 is stamped ‘byf 43’ on its slide indicating it was made from the Mauser manufacturing plant for Germany in 1943. Also it has the Nazi ‘swastika under eagle’ proof mark on its slide and ‘eagle over 135’ proof marks declaring that this firearm passed regulations and was indeed issued to German forces during the second world war. Again, this particular firearm is all matching having the ‘eagle over 135’ proof marks on all its individual parts. 

The firearm will also come with its matching WW2 Nazi leather holster. The holster has ‘1943’ stamped on its back along with an ‘eagle with swastika over WaA706’ proof mark again indicating it came from the Mauser plant in 1943 and issued to German forces during the war. Interestingly, the holster has had its original belt straps removed for a leather strap that can be used for cross draw. 

Lastly, the p38 will come with two (2) 8 round magazines. One of these magazines is just a post war reproduction Walther p1 magazine. It comes in a parkerize finish. The other magazine is much older, is blued in finish, and appears to have the Nazi proof mark of an ‘eagle over 88’ stamped on it towered to bottom of the magazine. This seconded magazine is the one I got with the purchase of this firearm and I believe it was brought back with the gun originally after the end of the war. 

The story I got with the purchase of this firearm is intriguing. It goes that the firearm belonged to a German officer stationed to the east front against the Russians. It was told that this firearm was used and carried in the battle of Stalingrad. However, I do not know how true this story is, it might have been made up but is still a nice story to tell when showcasing this particular piece. 

I am asking $ 1,200 or best offer for the whole package: the p38, the holster, both magazines, a soft gun bag, and a padlock. Need FFL transfer for purchase. Feel free to offer I do not mind you checking out the firearm first before purchase, just please no low ball offers. Also, might consider trading for quality 1911 or Smith and Wesson 44 magnum. You can contact me if interested either through the email associated through this listing or my calling 951- three ten- 02 zero four.

Thanks, David
